Getting Started

The code chunks below install and launch these R packages in R environment:


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
pacman::p_load(rgdal,spdep,tmap,sf,ggpubr,cluster,factoextra,NbClust,heatmaply,corrplot,psych,tidyverse,funModeling,ClustGeo)
```
:::


Below is the explanation for packages used in this Take-home exercise:

-   Spatial data handling

    -   **sf**, **rgdal** and **spdep**

-   Attribute data handling

    -   **tidyverse**, especially **readr**, **ggplot2** and **dplyr**

-   Choropleth mapping

    -   **tmap**

-   Multivariate data visualisation and analysis

    -   **coorplot**, **ggpubr**, and **heatmaply**

-   Cluster analysis

    -   **cluster**

    -   **ClustGeo**

## Data Import and Preparation

### Importing aspatial data into R environment

Since geo_export data set was downloaded in csv format, read_csv() function is used to read to import geo_export.csv


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
wp_nga<-read_csv("data/aspatial/geo_export.csv")
```

The original file name was called *Water_Point_Data_Exchange\_-PlusWPdx.csv, it has been rename to geo*\_export.csv for easy encoding.

From the above summary, we can see that the wp is in tibble data frame with 95008 rows and 70 columns.

Notice that this newly created data frame has a column called New Georeferenced Column which represents spatial data in text format. This is known as Well Known Text or wkt in short.

Next, we will need to convert this tibble data frame in wkt format into an sf data frame using sf package.

The below function st_as_sfc() function of sf package derives a new field called Geometry as shown in the below code chunks:


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
wp_nga$Geometry<-st_as_sfc(wp_nga$`New Georeferenced Column`)
```
:::


When opening the wp_nga data frame and scrolling to the right, we notice that there is a new field called Geometry added onto the data frame.

Next, st_sf() will be used to convert the tibble data frame into sf data frame as shown in the below code chunks:


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
wp_sf<-st_sf(wp_nga,crs=4326)
```
:::


We can check the summary of wp_sf data frame using the below code chunks with list() function:


::: {.cell}


Ensuring location data accuracy


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
wp_sf<-st_join(wp_sf,nga)
```
:::


We try to generate another data frame just to view the contents of two columns: `#clean_adm2` and `shapeName`.


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
wp_sf1<-select(wp_sf,c(`#clean_adm2`,`shapeName`))
```
:::


We notice that there are some discrepancies between the `#clean_adm2` and `shapeName`. For example, the Cameroon-Nigeria's territorial dispute area of Bakassi, in which there were supposedly 6 water points, were in fact under Akbapuyo, which is part of Nigeria. st_join() has helped us match the location of all water points based on actual area names based on provided coordinates to ensure location data accuracy instead of putting trust on the `#clean_adm2` declared, which may not be accurate.

![](images/Bakassi.png)

Thanks to this, in later part when we need to perform contiguity based method to find out list of neighbors for a particular area unit, we no longer face the issue of zero neighbors. More details will be mentioned in the later part.


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
wp_sf<-wp_sf%>%
  mutate(`#status_clean`=replace_na(`#status_clean`,"Unknown"))
```
:::

```{.r .cell-code}
freq(data=wp_sf,input="#status_clean")
```

Create another data frame for unknown water points:


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
wpt_unknown<-wp_sf%>%
  filter(`#status_clean`=="Unknown")
```
:::


Data frame for functional water points


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
wpt_functional<-wp_sf%>%
  filter(`#status_clean` %in% c("Functional","Functional but needs repair","Functional but not in use"))
```
:::


Data frame for non-functional water points


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
wpt_nonfunctional<-wp_sf%>%
  filter(`#status_clean` %in% c("Non-Functional","Non-Functional due to dry season","Abandoned/Decommissioned","Abandoned","Non functional due to dry season"))
```
:::


Data frame for water points with usage capacity of less than 1000


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
uc_lt1000<-wp_sf%>%
  filter(`usage_capacity`<1000)
```
:::


Data frame for water points with usage capacity of equal or more than 1000


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
uc_mt1000<-wp_sf%>%
  filter(`usage_capacity`>=1000)
```
:::


The below code chunks filter the `is_urban` field from the wp_sf data frame to TRUE and create a new data frame featuring all urban water points:


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
urban_wpt<-wp_sf%>%
  filter(`is_urban`=="TRUE")
```
:::


Data frame for rural water points


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
rural_wpt<-wp_sf%>%
  filter(`is_urban`=="FALSE")
```
:::


Data frame for hand pump water technology category


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
wp_sf<-wp_sf%>%
  mutate(`#water_tech_category`=replace_na(`#water_tech_category`,"Unknown"))
```
:::


Data frame for water points with Hand pump technology


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
handpump_wpt<-wp_sf%>%
  filter(`#water_tech_category`=="Hand Pump")
```
:::


Data frame for water points with Mechanized Pump technology


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
mechanized_wpt<-wp_sf%>%
  filter(`#water_tech_category`=="Mechanized Pump")
```
:::


Data frame for water points with Tapstand


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
tapstand_wpt<-wp_sf%>%
  filter(`#water_tech_category`=="Tapstand")
```
:::


Data frame for water points with Rope and Bucket


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
randb_wpt<-wp_sf%>%
  filter(`#water_tech_category`=="Rope and Bucket")
```
:::

::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
nga_wp<-nga %>%
  mutate(`total wpt`=lengths(st_intersects(nga,wp_sf)))%>%
  mutate(`wpt functional`=lengths(st_intersects(nga,wpt_functional)))%>%
  mutate(`wpt nonfunctional`=lengths(st_intersects(nga,wpt_nonfunctional)))%>%
  mutate(`wpt unknown`=lengths(st_intersects(nga,wpt_unknown)))%>%
  mutate(`wpt with capacity <1000`=lengths(st_intersects(nga,uc_lt1000)))%>%
  mutate(`wpt with capacity >=1000`=lengths(st_intersects(nga,uc_mt1000)))%>%
  mutate(`wpt urban`=lengths(st_intersects(nga,urban_wpt)))%>%
  mutate(`wpt rural`=lengths(st_intersects(nga,rural_wpt)))%>%
  mutate(`wpt hand pump`=lengths(st_intersects(nga,handpump_wpt)))%>%
  mutate(`wpt mechanized pump`=lengths(st_intersects(nga,mechanized_wpt)))%>%
  mutate(`wpt tapstand`=lengths(st_intersects(nga,tapstand_wpt)))%>%
  mutate(`wpt rope and bucket`=lengths(st_intersects(nga,randb_wpt)))
```
:::

::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
nga_wp<-nga_wp%>%
  mutate(`pct functional`=`wpt functional`/`total wpt`)%>%
  mutate(`pct nonfunctional`=`wpt nonfunctional`/`total wpt`)%>%
  mutate(`pct unknown`=`wpt unknown`/`total wpt`)%>%
  mutate(`pct capacity<1000`=`wpt with capacity <1000`/`total wpt`)%>%
  mutate(`pct capacity>=1000`=`wpt with capacity >=1000`/`total wpt`)%>%
  mutate(`pct urban`=`wpt urban`/`total wpt`)%>%
  mutate(`pct rural`=`wpt rural`/`total wpt`)%>%
  mutate(`pct hand pump`=`wpt hand pump`/`total wpt`)%>%
  mutate(`pct mechanized pump`=`wpt mechanized pump`/`total wpt`)%>%
  mutate(`pct tapstand`=`wpt tapstand`/`total wpt`)%>%
  mutate(`pct rope and bucket`=`wpt rope and bucket`/`total wpt`)
```
:::


Filter out regions without any water points.

The below code chunks filter regions without water points. In regions without water point , percentage of different attributes becomes 0 because dividing by 0.


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
nga_wp<-nga_wp%>%
  filter(`total wpt`!=0)
```

Preparing a choropleth map


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
tm_shape(nga_wp)+
  tm_polygons(c("total wpt","pct nonfunctional","pct rural","pct hand pump"),style="jenks")+
  tm_facets(sync=TRUE,ncol=2)+
  tm_legend(legend.position=c("right","bottom"))+
  tm_layout(outer.margins = 0,asp=0)
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](Take-hom_Ex2_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-36-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::


From the above maps, in the south west region of Nigeria, we notice a worrying trend that although they had less number of water points, the percentage of non-functional water points tend to be higher.

```{.r .cell-code}
nga_wp1<-nga_wp%>%
  st_set_geometry(NULL)

```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](Take-hom_Ex2_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-38-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::


From the above graph, we can notice the perfect negative correlation between percentage of water points in rural area and percentage of water points in urban area (which fits our understanding that an area can only be categorized as either urban or rural, but cannot be both), percentage of water points with usage capacity \<1000 and percentage of water points with usage capacity \>=1000, percentage of water points with usage capacity \<1000 and percentage of mechanized pump. In other words, modern mechanized pump has higher usage capacity of at least 1000, while traditional hand pump can only provide usage capacity of up to 300 in the case of Nigeria.

At the same time, we also observe high correlation between percentage of functional and non-functional water point. This also fits our understanding that a water point should only be classified as function, non-functional or unknown.

Therefore, we can drop attribute such as pct urban (percentage of water points in urban area), pct mechanized (percentage of water points with mechanized pumps), pct capacity \<1000 (percentage of water points with usage of less than 1000), pct capacity \>=1000 (percentage of water points with usage capacity of at least 1000) as well as pct functional (percentage of functional water points). In fact, those attributes that we keep for our cluster analysis are in line with the objective of our study and research. We would like to solve problems related to non-functional water points, water points with outdated technology, water points in rural area where the population may have difficulties accessing quality source of water. This is what we would like to achieve.

Computing hierarchical clustering


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
hclust_ward<-hclust(proxmat, method="ward.D")
```
:::

::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
plot(hclust_ward,cex=0.005)
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](Take-hom_Ex2_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-45-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::


Selecting the optimal clustering algorithm


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
m<-c("average","single","complete","ward")
names(m)<-c("average","single","complete","ward")
ac<-function(x){agnes(nga_att,method=x)$ac}
map_dbl(m,ac)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}
```
  average    single  complete      ward 
0.9371130 0.8674494 0.9670278 0.9950800 
```
:::
:::


Regarding the above output, we can see that Ward's method provides the strongest clustering structure among the four methods assessed. Therefore, in the subsequent analysis, only Ward's method will be used.

Determining Optimal Clusters


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
set.seed(12345)
gap_stat<-clusGap(nga_att,FUN=hcut,nstart=25,K.max=10,B=50)
print(gap_stat,method="firstmax")
```
